[2] Sierra Leone: lockdown in eastern mining district
Date: Wed 10 Dec 2014
Source: Daily Mail, AFP (Agence France-Presse) report [edited]
http://www.dailymail.co.uk/wires/afp/article-2869123/Ebola-lockdown-eastern-Sierra-Leone-mining-district.html


Ebola lockdown in eastern Sierra Leone mining district
------------------------------------------------------
Sierra Leone authorities imposed a 2-week lockdown on the eastern diamond mining district of Kono [Wed 10 Dec 2014] after 8 new cases of Ebola were confirmed in 1 day. The lockdown will limit residents' movements until [Tue 23 Dec 2014]. The decision to impose a lockdown was taken at a meeting of traditional rulers known as the Council of Paramount Chiefs, its chairman Paul Saquee told reporters.

The WHO said investigators sent to the remote Kono district last week found Ebola patients dying in a hospital unequipped to deal with the virus. It said in 11 days, teams had buried 87 bodies, including a nurse, an ambulance driver and a janitor who had removed bodies from the hospital as they piled up. As of [Tue 9 Dec 2014], the Kono district, with a population of 350 000, officially had 123 confirmed cases of Ebola. But the director of disease control for Sierra Leone's health ministry, Dr. Amara Jambai, suggested that number was far too low.

Olu Olushayo, the WHO's coordinator in Sierra Leone, said Sierra Leone officials, the US Centers for Disease Control [and Prevention -- CDC] and other organizations were sending staff and equipment to Kono. It said the International Red Cross would quickly build a new Ebola treatment center and disinfect the hospital. The WHO national Ebola coordinator Olu Olushayo, said rapid reaction has so far helped contain the cases of Ebola virus to about half of the 15 chiefdoms in Kono.

Freelance journalist Emmanuel Lebbie said: "People are moving freely within towns and villages, but are not allowed to go beyond the district itself." Most people were remaining indoors and while shops were open, the markets were largely empty of consumers. Only essential vehicles such as fuel-carrying tankers, military, police, NGO workers and UN-associated vehicles were allowed through heavily monitored checkpoints into the district. Private and commercial vehicles and motor cycle taxis are barred, and mining activity has ceased, one mines monitor reported. ... -- more

